\begin{document}
\chapter{\\ORIGINS OF THE RETROTRANSPOSON ANTISENSE BIAS}
\doublespace\large{

The phenomenon of non-randomly distributed RTs facilitates studies into the variable effects that RTs impart on genes. Effects that may be accompanied by phenotypic changes. This is only true, however, if the altered distribution of RTs within genes is due to forces acting on phenotypes (i.e.: selection) as opposed to other mechanisms such as genetic drift or RT mobilization. Studies attempting to determine the mechanistic underpinnings leading to changes in RT distribution over time have identified that selection is indeed the major mechanism responsible [REFs, and \ref{sec:dist}].

Despite the knowledge that some form of selection acts on RTs in general, there are two major questions that are yet to be resolved, i) is the altered distribution of RTs, specifically within genes, due to selection? and ii) are the selective forces acting on RTs positive or negative (purifying)? Although the first question (i) may seem like an unnecessary detail to pursue, it is vital to future studies attempting to discern the phenotypic effects of RTs on genes. It is important because there are altered distributions of RTs within genes that, if they are due to selection, can be used to predict the phenotypic impact of future insertions. If instead the altered distribution of RTs in genes is due to integration, then these predictions would be unfounded, and perhaps misleading. Though it is unlikely, it is possible that the altered distributions within genes are due to integration bias. This distinction must be determined before further analyses on phenotypic associations with RTs distributions are analyzed.

The RT antisense bias (AS bias) is a powerful example of altered distributions of RTs within genes that can be used to delineate between effects of selection versus integration. AS bias is the tendency of RTs to be present in the antisense (AS) orientation within genes more often than the sense (S) orientation. An interesting feature of AS bias is that it peaks near transcription start sites (TSS), as do the total number of RTs \cite{Medstrand2002}.

This recurring altered distribution of AS bias towards transcription start sites may indicate an mechanism of selection, however it may also indicate a preference for integration locations. An argument for the enrichment of  RTs  near the TSS is that there is increased open chromatin near the TSS and therefore increased accesibility to the L1 ORF2p endonuclease [REF]. However, if open chromatin was the reason for the increase in RTs then this preference should be replicated in both the sense and antisense orientations. Moreover, since L1 ORF2p endonucleases bind dsDNA, there should be no preference for integration due to single-strand accesibility [REF]. Also, it has been shown that RTs in the sense orientation effect transcription of the coincident gene, while RTs in the antisense orientation have little to no effect [REFs]. For these reasons, it was hypothesized that the AS bias of RTs in genes was due to selection.   

To distinguish whether AS bias was truly a result of    selection over time or if it was due to integration, the distribution of relatively recent Alu insertions were examined, as well as the change in AS bias over evolutionary time. 
    
%1000 genomes by population and Faulkner data
%ASbias upon insertion
\section{Retrotransposon Antisense Bias and the Process of Integration}
\subsection{Young AS and S Alu are Present in Equal Proportions}
\label{sec:youngas}
Newly inserted RTs should be equally represented in the sense (S) and antisense (AS) orientations if selection is the driving force of AS bias in genes. Alu and L1 insert at a higher rate than SVA, and therefore have a larger sample size of elements with low residence times in the population (i.e.: young). For this reason, Alu and L1 were studied to examine the AS bias of newly inserted elements. 

Two samples of young RTs (Alu and L1) were used for this analysis (\textit{a} and \textit{b}) filtered groups of Alu that were annotated as insertions in the \num{1000} genomes project \cite{Stewart2011}, and (\textit{c}) Alu and L1 annotated as newly identified germline insertions \cite{Baillie2011, Bundo2013}. Both groups represent RTs that are polymorphic with relatively small residence times in the population. Here, polymorphic refers to presence or absence of the entire element where any mutations within the element are irrelevant. 

Alu in groups \textit{a} and \textit{b} were initially identified in the 1000 genomes project as being polymorphic between individuals \cite{Stewart2011}. The allele frequencies of these elements were calculated from three populations; Yoruban (YRI); European (CEU); and Chinese/Japanese (CHBJPT) \cite{Stewart2011}. For the current analysis, 1000 genomes annoted Alu were separated into two groups: \textit{a}) population-specific Alu (i.e.: Allele Frequency (AF) > 0 in only one population), and \textit{b}) Alu present among two or more populations. Group \textit{c} elements were derived from three individuals that were examined for non-reference Alu insertions in various somatic tissues. The mean AFs of group \textit{a} Alu were 0.091 ($\pm$0.071), 0.067 ($\pm$0.047), and 0.070 ($\pm$0.067) in YRI, CEU, and CHBJPT respectively. To identify the mean AF of group \textit{b} Alu, the maximum population-specific AF was identified per element. The average of these maximum AFs was significantly higher than the population-specific sets 0.279($\pm$0.16) (Wilcoxon rank sum p$_{, YRI}$ < 1.3e-184; p$_{, CEU}$ < 2.6e-62; p$_{, CHBJPT}$ < 8.5e-49). The AFs of group \textit{c} Alu were similar in all three populations (figure \ref{fig:AF_3d}). Since AFs are correlated with residence times in the population \cite{Li1975}, these AFs indicate that group \textit{a} Alu have shorter residence times (younger) than group \textit{b}.

    %Figure 
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{AF_3d.png}
        \caption{\normalsize{\textbf{Similar AFs of shared Alu\\} Correlations of  Allele Frequencies (AF) bettween CEU (European), YRI (Yoruban), and Chinese/Japanese (CHBJPT) populations.}}
        \label{fig:AF_3d}
    \end{figure}
    
Although the allele frequencies of group \textit{c} RTs were unknown, they were identified in Baillie et. al. as being present in the germline insertions. Since group \textit{a} and \textit{c} RTs all represent young polymorphic insertions the counts were combined across all groups to reduce type II error by increasing sample size (table \ref{table:youngasbias}). The probability of choosing an AS RT in this combined group was tested versus an expected probability of 0.50 using the binomial sign test. The hypothesis that young insertions had an AS bias equal to 0.50 could not be rejected (p(AS) = 0.50 ; \num{95}\% CI = 0.47 -- 0.53; p = 0.84). It was noted, that there may have been a bias imparted to the calculation by combining both group \text{a} and \textit{c} RTs. Group \textit{a} RTs were therefore tested separately, despite a reduction in power, and also  did not have a p(AS) significantly different from 0.5 (p(AS) = 0.53; \num{95}\% CI = 0.48 -- 0.57; p = 0.20). Although the results of insignificance indicated that young RTs may not have an AS bias, the null hypothesis can not be proved, only rejected \cite{Popper1959,Wilckinson2013}. Therefore, young RTs were tested against the AS bias of the reference RTs, to determine if the AS bias of young elements was significantly different from the bias that is often cited in the literature \cite{Zhang2011}. 


%AS bias of new insertions
