\label{table:alul1ref}
\end{table}

%TPRT
\subsection{AS bias is present in transposons integrated by non-TPRT mechanisms}

The evidence presented in section \ref{sec:youngas} has shown that there is no discernible AS bias upon integration, indicating that the process of Alu integration (ie: TPRT) does not likely contribute to AS bias. Alu, L1, and SVA are all integrated through the process of TPRT, and all have significant differences in the proportion of AS and S elements. Therefore, it is pertinent to this study to determine if AS bias is restricted to elements which are integrated by TPRT. The null hypothesis that transposons inserted by non-TPRT mechanisms had equal proportions of sense and antisense elements was examined. Similar to Alu, a pooled group of DNA transposons had a significant increase of AS elements over S elements (probability of AS = \num{0.540}; \num{95}\% CI = \num{0.538} - \num{0.543}; p < \num{1.64}e\num{-190}), indicating that AS bias is not restricted to the RT-specific form of integration, TPRT.

%AS bias changes over evolutionary time
\section{Antisense Bias Increases Over Evolutionary Time}
Since Alu present in the reference genome have a significantly larger proportion of AS elements than newly integrated elements, it is likely that this change in proportion was due to a progressive action over time. It is therefore important to examine the change in AS bias over time.

    %Figure pAS_subfamily Alu
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{pAS_alu_2.pdf}
        \caption{\normalsize{\textbf{Change in pAS Across Reference Alu\\}AS/S ratios were calculated for each Alu subfamily and plotted versus the mean deviation from the subfamily consensus sequence (millidiv). AS bias was regressed on millidiv to obtain the fitted line (blue; p = 0.38).}}
        \label{fig:pAS_subfam}
    \end{figure}
    
\subsection{Antisense bias of Alu is Constant across Reference Subfamilies}
To examine the change of p(AS) over time, AS bias of Alu and L1 were individually examined after separation into their predefined subfamilies. The relative age of a subfamily is often measured as the average distance of all elements within a subfamily from the respective consensus sequence (milliDiv). Elements within a subfamily have similar residence times in the genome [REFs].  Millidiv was therefore used as a measurement of time where smaller values of millidiv corresponded to younger elements with less residence time in the population, and larger millidiv corresponded to older elements with longer residence times. AS bias was examined across Alu subfamilies ranked by millidiv (figure \ref{fig:pAS_subfam}). There was a slight increase in AS bias with increasing millidiv, though, this increase was not signficant (slope: 4.1e-04; F-test p = \num{0.38}). 

\subsection{Antisense bias of L1 Increases Across Reference Subfamilies}

    %Figure pAS_subfamily L1
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{pAS_l1_2.pdf}
        \caption{\normalsize{\textbf{Change in pAS Across Reference L1\\}AS/S ratios were calculated for each L1 subfamily and plotted versus the mean deviation from the subfamily consensus sequence (millidiv). AS bias was regressed on millidiv to obtain the fitted line (blue; p < \num{2.66}e{-06}).}}
        \label{fig:pAS_l1_2}
    \end{figure}
    
Although Alu and L1 both have a signficant AS bias in the genome, it is possible that they are undergoing different degrees of selection. As pol-II promoted transcripts, L1 have the potential to disrupt expression more substantially than Alu [REF]. L1 have also been evolving since before the split of  marsupials and eutherians, as opposed to Alu which have only been present in the primate lineages, therefore the extent of time that is covered by the L1 subfamilies is effectively longer than that of Alu [REFs]. For these reasons, it is more likely to observe a change in AS bias in L1 as opposed to Alu. This is evidenced by the finding that the AS bias of L1 is significantly larger than that of Alu (prop AS$_{L1}$ =  0.656; prop AS$_{Alu}$ = 0.549 ; p < 2.2e-16).

L1 AS bias was examined across subfamilies ordered by millidiv. Contrary to the findings in Alu, there was a significant trend towards an increase in AS bias over time (F-test p < \num{2.66}e{-06}) (figure \ref{fig:pAS_l1_2}). These results indicate that, as opposed to a static property of the integration, AS bias increases dynamically over time. 

 
\subsection{Antisense bias of Alu increases quickly over evolutionary time}
The findings so far have shown that AS and S RTs have no bias upon integration, however there is an AS bias of Alu in the reference genome. For Alu, this AS bias in reference Alu was independent of the age of the subfamily. It was therefore hypothesized that AS bias in Alu was achieved rapidly after integration.  To examine the change of AS proportion on shorter time scales than the previous analysis, p(AS) of young Alu were compared to p(AS) of Alu that were shared among all three populations (group \textit{b}). Shared Alu were assumed to have longer residence times in the genome than young Alu because shared elements must have integrated prior to the split of YRI, CEU, and CHBJPT, while young elements were assumed to have inserted after the split. The higher average allele frequencies of shared Alu compared to group population-specific Alu substantiates this assumption (section \ref{sec:youngas}). Although the shared Alu had a mean frequency of 0.28, there were elements with allele frequencies of 1 within a specific population (figure \ref{fig:shared_freq}). The proportion of AS in the young subset of Alu was significantly smaller than polymorphic Alu that were shared among all three populations ($propAS_{\text{young}}$ = 0.48; $propAS_{\text{shared}}$ = 0.54; \num{95}\% CI = \num{-0.11} - \num{-0.02}; p < \num{0.01}). This indicates that the change to AS bias of Alu occured quickly over evolutionary time.

    %Figure pAS
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{shared_freq.pdf}
        \caption{\normalsize{\textbf{Allele Frequencies of Alu that are Shared Between All Populations\\} Many polymorphic Alu identified in the 1000 genomes project were shared between YRI, CEU, and CHBJPT. The count of Alu is plotted as a function of the maximum allele frequency between YRI, CEU, and CHBJPT.}}
        \label{fig:shared_freq}
    \end{figure}


These results indicate that Alu are initially integrated with no AS bias, AS and S Alu are then differentially maintained setting up the reference AS bias. And this event occurs relatively quickly on evolutionary time scales (ie: prior to fixation). It must be noted that this same hypothesis could be true for L1 as well, though there are not enough counts of shared L1 to test this hypothesis.


%Signs of purifying selection
\section{Evidence of Purifying Selection on S and AS Retrotransposons}
The results so far have shown that AS bias is not present upon integration but increases over time, as would be expected under a model of selection. If selection within genes is playing a role in this change in AS bias, there are three working hypotheses that can be tested: \textit{1}) Antisense RTs undergo positive selection within genes, \textit{2}) Sense RTs undergo negative (purifying) selection within genes, and \textit{3}) Both (\textit{1}) and (\textit{2}) are true. Previous reports have indicated that Alu undergo purifying selection on a genome-wide level \cite{Stewart2011}. However, Lander et al. have proposed that the increase of Alu in GC-rich regions was due to positive selection, though gave no experimental evidence to support these conclusions \cite{Lander2001}. Neither of these studies have addressed the selection of RTs within gene boundaries, which is important to study due to the potential distruptions of RTs directly on transcription as well as regulation of both transcription and translation [REFs].

In 1975 Li calculated that on average, deleterious alleles have shorter residence times in a population. In other words, they will be younger than neutral or advantageous alleles \cite{Li1975}. The logic behind this finding lies in that, in populations of equal size, an allele is more likely to be passed on to the next generation if it is neutral or positive compared to an allele that is deleterious. The neutral or positive allele will therefore remain in the population longer, accumulating a longer residence time in the genome. Meanwhile, new alleles, both advantageous and deleterious will continually appear. While the advantageous alleles are retained, the deleterious alleles will continually be lost, with only young alleles that have replaced them remaining present. Therefore at any discrete point in time, the deleterious alleles will be younger on average than the advantageous or neutral alleles.

         %Figure 
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{selection5_3.png}
        \caption{\textbf{AS bias of Alu across gene deciles\\}
        More here
        }
        \label{fig:l1age}
    \end{figure}

Using the rationale presented in Li, 1975; the relative force of selection can be compared between two, otherwise equal, alleles by calculating their respective residence times in a population. RTs within a subfamily are an optimal sample to study selective forces, since they have the advantage of being amplified at similar points in time [REF]. Therefore, elements of the same subfamily should have similar residence times in the population when calculated as millidiv. However, if there are deviations in the forces of selection between subsets of the subfamily (i.e: AS versus S) , then the residence times in the population should be unequal. An example of the hypothesis is presented in figure \ref{fig:l1age}. Here is shown the AS bias of Alu in two regions of genes, one region with a large AS bias, and one region with no AS bias. The hypotheses of selection underlying these distributions are listed at the bottom of the figure. 


\subsection{Purifying selection of RTs in genes}
Since Alu and L1 showed different changes in AS bias over time, it was expected that the age ranges associated with differences in AS bias would also be different. It was expected that despite the apparent AS bias, Alu would have relatively similar ages between AS and S elements, since they likely were selected on relatively soon after integration.

         %Figure 
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{l1_age_anova.pdf}
        \caption{\textbf{Age of L1 By Subfamily\\}
        More here
        }
        \label{fig:l1ageanova}
    \end{figure}

It was important to determine if the age of an L1 element was contingent on the placement within the genome (i.e.: intergenic, AS within genes, or S within genes). To examine the associated of age with placement, millidiv was regressed on dummy variables representing each possible placement of the element (equation \ref{l1anova}). Since each subfamily has a different mean millidiv, and therefore would contribute differently to the calculation irrespective of placement, separate equations were calculated for each subfamily. This method of analysing the subfamilies separately was chosen instead of adding the subfamilies into the model as a random effect because it was important to observe how the estimates changed across increasingly aged subfamilies. A p-value was calculated for each regression equation and plotted as a function of the average millidiv in the entire subfamily within genes (figure \ref{fig:l1ageanova}). 79 of the 114 subfamilies had millidiv values that were significantly associated with location after Bonferroni correction for multiple testing ( $\alpha$  = 4.3e-04; Appendix table \ref{table:l1subvalues}). Moreover, the significance of these results increased with increasing age of the subfamily as a whole. These results indicated that there were different selection biases present depending on the placement of the RT.
    %Linear Regression Equation 1 : L1 anova
    \begin{equation}
    \label{l1anova}
         millidiv = \beta location_{subfamily, i}  +  \epsilon
    \end{equation}


    %         %Figure 
    %\begin{figure}[!ht]
    %    \centering
    %    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{l1_intolder.pdf}
    %    \caption{\textbf{Intergenic L1 are older than L1 in Genes\\}
    %    More here
    %    }
    %    \label{fig: l1intolder}
    %\end{figure}
    %
    
To determine if the association between location and millidiv was effected more by regions within genes versus intergenic, or sense versus antisense.  77 subfamilies had elements that were significantly different in age between intergenic and within gene regions (tests =114 ; Bonferroni corrected $\alpha$ = 4.4e-04). 76 of these 77 subfamilies were older in intergenic regions than within genes. This substantiates the hypothesis that L1 retrotransposons undergo purifying selection within genes. 10 subfamilies had significant differences in age between AS and S orientations, 7 of which were older in the antisense orientation. 

    %             %Figure 
    %\begin{figure}[!ht]
    %    \centering
    %    \includegraphics[width=0.5\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{l1_senseolder.pdf}
    %    \caption{\textbf{Sense and Antisense L1 \\}
    %    More here
    %    }
    %    \label{fig: l1senseolder}
    %\end{figure}

Alu were similarly analyzed for differences in age depending on position and orientation. Similar to L1, there was an increasingly significant effect of difference in age between regions within increasing age of the subfamily (figure \ref{fig:aluageanova}). Interestingly 14 of the 14 subfamilies that were significantly different in age between intergenic and within genes were all older intergenically (tests = 36 ; Bonferroni corrected  $\alpha$ = 1.4e-03). This replicates the findings from L1 showing that both L1 and Alu are under purifying selection in genes when compared to the same subfamilies in intergenic regions. Similarly 20 of the 20 subfamilies that were significantly different in age between S and AS orientations were older in the AS orientation. 


         %Figure 
    \begin{figure}[!ht]
        \centering
        \includegraphics[width=0.8\textwidth,natwidth=610,natheight=642]{alu_age_anova.pdf}
        \caption{\textbf{Age of Alu By Subfamily\\}
        More here
        }
        \label{fig:aluageanova}
    \end{figure}
  

  
