\subsection{Lack of Purifying Selection of RTs on ChrY}
To further test whether purifying or positive selection were acting on RTs within genes, we took advantage of the differing rates of selection on chrX, chrY, and the autosomes. It's been shown previously that rates of selection are faster on chrX than the autosomes, and faster on the autosomes than chrY [REF]. For this reason, and for the overall lack of purifying selection on chrY it was hypothesized that the age of RTs would increase in age from chrX to autosomes to chrY, within groups of RTs. First, to have a broad idea of the age of RTs across chromosomes, each location group was analyzed with all subfamilies aggregated together. Although aggregating all subfamilies into a single measure was expected to wash out a lot of the signal, there were significant differences between chromosomes when analyzed this way (table \ref{table:chrxyage}). 

